ξ 42 During Antonius’ absence from Rome there ap- peared on the scene the man, who was destined to in- herit not merely the name, but the power of Oaesar. The first interview of Antonius and O. Octavianus, whom Cicero does not yet mention in the second Philippic, was none of the friendliest. Antonius re- fused to deliver to him Oaesar's remaining estate, or to give an account of the purposes to which his inherit- ance had been applied. Hereupon Octavianus offered Oaesar's lands for sale, and also devoted his own patri- mony to the payment of Gaesar's legacies to the people, and to the exhibition of magnificent games.
